title: For Sale:  Walther Model 9 Pistol .25 ACP Caliber
postcontent: Collectible Type II, Model 9b, pre-WWII pistol (6-shot capacity), upgraded nickel finish, with acid-etched engraving on the slide. The serial number is 603253, which would make the production year somewhere in the late 1920's or early 1930's. As there are no military or other nazi symbols on this pistol, it is probably in the 1930-1932 era. There is some scuffing to the finish, so I would have to say that this would be about a 75%-80% pistol. I have done a superficial cleaning to this pistol, without a full disassembly, and it appears to be functional. However, I would urge any prospective buyer to take it to a competent gunsmith for a full field stripping and cleaning before attempting to fire this pistol. Sale of this pistol MUST be done in strict compliance with all Federal, State, and local firearms laws and regulations. This means the transfer can only be done through authorized FFL dealer(s). The P-40 has six main component groups: barrel, slide, frame, firing mechanism, grip, and magazine. The barrel is made of SAE 4140 Ordnance steel heat treated to 47 HRC. title: For Sale:  6.5 DUTCH MANNLICHER
postcontent:
This Rifle is definitely of interest to collectors of Mannlicher rifles and of Dutch arms. THIS WEAPON WAS TAKEN WITH CLIP AND FIVE BULLETS FROM A SURRENDERING CAMP GUARD IN GERMANY DURING WWII.     These rifles, and Dutch weapons in general, aren't at all common in this country since there were few GI bring-backs (Holland was neutral in WWI and an ally in WWII, so it would not have been legal for GIs to bring back Dutch guns even if they obtained them); further, Holland never sold any large numbers of rifles off as surplus. 
Because that carbine is unusual, I would WAG a value at $350 or so, but will be happy to be corrected by anyone with better knowledge.

It is a Dutch Artillery Carbine, made by Hembrug Artillerie - Inrichten (the Dutch state arsenal) in 1918. Those carbines were carried across the back while the artilleryman was serving the gun.

For a small country, the Dutch made/adopted an amazing variety of carbines, at least 12, plus other models for the KNIL (Koninlijk Nederlands Indisch Leger - Royal Dutch Indies Army). All were based on the Model 1895 Mannlicher and fired the 6.5x53R cartridge also used by Rumania. Loading was by the typical Mannlicher en-bloc clip which entered the magazine and remained until empty at which point it dropped out the bottom.

Hembrug is a Netherlands State arsenal and the picture illustrates Holland's Karabijn M1895. The "W" cipher on the butt stock was that of Queen Wilhelmina. The design was Mannlicher's, which is immediately evident given the bolt release among other things. Caliber is normally 6.5mm but a few were re-barrelled to 7.92mm.

Ammo (6.5X53R Dutch) and clips are available; I purchased both from Old Western Scrounger Inc, which I believe has been purchased by someone else but still is in business. Like most military long guns of the era, you will find that this gun tends to shoot high.

The $350 value would have been right in the ball park pre-Obama. I believe they may be worth a little more today; perhaps as much as $450

I AM SELLING ALL FOR $350, OWN A PIECE OF HISTORY !!!!
CALL BILL AT 423 - 503 - 2323
